late 1990s are mobilised as discussants on the question of subjectivity. Four contemporary playtexts and their performances are examined in depth: Sarah Kane’s Crave and 4.48 Psychosis, Ed Thomas’s Stone City Blue and Tim Crouch’s ENGLAND. Through these case studies, Delgado-García demonstrates alternative ways of engaging theoretically with character, and elucidating a range of subjective figures beyond identity and individuality. Alongside these analyses, the book traces a large body of work that has experimented with speech attribution since the early twentieth-century. This is a timely contribution to contemporary theatre scholarship, which demonstrates that character remains a malleable and politically-salient notion in which understandings of subjectivity are still being negotiated.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aTheaterzGreat Britainy21st century. 0aTheater--Great Britain--21st century. 4aCharakter. 4aPolitik der Ästhetik. 4aPostdramatisches Theater. 4aSubjektivität. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Drama.2bisacsh  aCharacter.  aPolitics of Aesthetics.  aPostdramatic Theatre.  aSubjectivity.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2015 Part 1z978311076251808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2015z978311070098508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2015z9783110439687oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Studies 2015z9783110438673oZDB-23-DKU0 cEPUBz97831104112250 cprintz978311040390940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311033391640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110333916423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110333916/original  a978-3-11-070098-5  DG Plus eBook-Package 2015b20